### Which @angular/* package(s) are relevant/related to the feature request?

core

### Description

It would be convenient if a resource derived from a snapshot was writable, even if reloading isn't possible.

### Proposed solution

based on the current implementation, and that of `BaseWritableResource`/`ResourceImpl`, I imagine it would become something along the lines of:

```typescript
export function resourceFromSnapshots<T>(source: () => ResourceSnapshot<T>): WritableResource<T> {
  return new SnapshotResource(linkedSignal(source));
}

class SnapshotResource<T> implements WritableResource<T> {
  readonly value: WritableSignal<T>;

  constructor(readonly snapshot: WritableSignal<ResourceSnapshot<T>>) {
    this.value = linkedSignal(() => {
      if (this.state.status === 'error') {
        throw new ResourceValueError(this.state.error);
      }
      return this.state.value;
    });
    this.value.set = this.set.bind(this);
    this.value.update = this.update.bind(this);
  }

  private get state(): ResourceSnapshot<T> {
    return this.snapshot();
  }

  readonly status = computed(() => this.state.status);
  readonly error = computed(() => (this.state.status === 'error' ? this.state.error : undefined));
  readonly isLoading = computed(
    () => this.state.status === 'loading' || this.state.status === 'reloading',
  );

  private isValueDefined = computed(
    () => this.state.status !== 'error' && this.state.value !== undefined,
  );

  hasValue(this: T extends undefined ? this : never): this is WritableResource<Exclude<T, undefined>>;
  hasValue(): boolean;
  hasValue(): boolean {
    return this.isValueDefined();
  }

  set(value: T): void {
    this.snapshot.set({ status: 'local', value });
  }

  update(updateFn: (value: T) => T): void {
    this.set(updateFn(untracked(this.value)));
  }

  asReadonly(): Resource<T> {
    return this;
  }

  reload(): boolean {
    return false;
  }
}
```

There might be a more efficient way to implement it, like keeping the snapshot as a regular `Signal` and directly updating the `value` and `status` fields, but writing directly to the snapshot seemed more in line with the `set` implementation in `ResourceImpl`.

### Alternatives considered

If expanding the current `SnapshotResource` to implement the `WritableResource` interface isn't a good idea/possible, it could also be its own separate `WritableSnapshotResource` with an analogous `writableResourceFromSnapshots` method.

